I had the privilege of observing a number of grizzly bears last Monday at the Khutzeymateen Grizzly Bear Sanctuary.  Two moms had triplets.  One of the mothers sensed some type of danger in the forest, called her cubs, and ran further down the beach with them.  Shortly afterwards, she laid down and nursed the cubs, who were about a year old.  They then went back to eating grass, which I was told has a relatively high protein content.  The cub in the first photo I'm posting was also digging in the dirt near the beach, possibly for clams or some other type of food.

Important Features for Identification:

general:
-broad skulls with narrow muzzle and large jaw hinges
-short and rounded black or greyish-brown claws
-small, rounded ears
-large variation in coat colour depending on region (white, blonde, cinnamon, light brown, dark brown, jet black).
size:
-males 57-250 kg 
-females 41-170 kg 
habitat:
-prefer relatively inaccessible terrain, thick under story vegetation and large quantities of food. 

Notes: Due to the variation in coat colour, Black Bears can be mistaken for Grizzle Bears but can be distinguished by their smaller size, less concave skulls, shorter claws and absence of shoulder hump.

During our grizzly viewing trip, Glendale Cove harbored about 30 grizzly bears, females with and without cubs. The estuary was chock full of pink salmon. Note that one of the sows had four (adorable) cubs. This family came close to our boat on its own while we were stationary. At the time, British Columbia still allowed for trophy hunting of grizzly bears. The three-way interaction between female bears with their cubs, male bears and tourists has been studied scientifically: http://insight.cumbria.ac.uk/id/eprint/878/1/Nevin_EvaluationOfA.pdf

A daily family visit for years. They love to eat spring grass, dandelions, clover and leaves… Turnips, not so much! When grazing it sounds like they’re crunching apples! 
City-folk who move here need to remember that wildlife live here, and to bring dogs indoors while bears are nearby. (Dogs go nuts around bears). Keep them leashed on walks and get the heck away when you spot cubs. 
Also, don’t jog past wildlife like you own the place. Expect to be clawed or nipped if you do. Even domestic dogs might automatically nip those who run past their yard, the same way that they chase car and bike tires. The movement is irresistible and tantalizing.  It’s their nature to protect territory.

Very young Mom-bear sent cub up tree, then ambled over and sniffed our contented vole-hunting-cat while he slept on a chair. Cat ‘flew’ a hissy-fit and set a boundary on his favourite sunning boulder, where mom bear sniffed him again and peed a tinkle when cat raised his hackles again. Mom-bear then slowly walked down the garden boulders and peed a bunch along the bottom edge by our bear-grazing lawn. Perhaps a new limit boundary for the cub. Our cat may look like a skinny little bear-playmate to the cub. (Later noticed bear saliva on cat’s fur. Was told bears will lick you in passing too. Like some dogs do. Perhaps they derive info this way. )

When they reached the common migration trail at the end of the yard, Mom-bear clawed a tree. Probably another message.

We witnessed a tragedy today. This baby bear was killed by a human and their vehicle, a hit and run. We passed by in the opposite direction shortly after, turned around and came back. I picked him up and sobbing, I carried him off of the highway. He weighed slightly less than my 5 year old daughter. His body was still warm and supple. His eyes still looked clear. I saw the impact wound on his forehead and prayed that his death was quick and not too painful. I checked his sex and was glad that he was not a potential birther. Another car stopped after turning around and said that they saw his mother in a nearby meadow. I laid him in a beautiful spot, placed some violets on him and said a prayer.

Lone female grizzly bear foraging along the bank of West Cracroft Island. This one was seen pulling berries off shrubs and swimming. Others were overturning rocks looking for marine invertebrates. 

Grizzly Bear (Ursus arctos ssp. horribilis) characteristics:
Grizzly bears are excellent swimmers. 
A pronounced muscular hump appears on adult grizzlies' shoulders; black bears do not have this hump.
A "dished in" profile of their face with short, rounded ears, whereas a black bear has a straight face profile and longer ears.
A grizzly bear can also be identified by its rump, which is lower than its shoulders; a black bear's rump is higher than its shoulders.
A grizzly bear's front claws measure about 2–4 inches in length; a black bear's claws measure about 1–2 inches in length. Claws are longer than an American black bear’s and are adapted for digging.

Although the once-abundant California grizzly bear appears prominently on the state flag of California and was the symbol of the Bear Flag Republic before California's admission to the Union in 1850, that subspecies or population is Extinct. The last known grizzlies in California were killed in the Sierra foothills east of Fresno in the early 1920s  :-(

Hibernation: Grizzly bears hibernate for 5 to 7 months each year, except where the climate is warm (the California grizzly did not hibernate). During this time, female grizzly bears give birth to their offspring, who then consume milk from their mother and gain strength for the remainder of the hibernation period. To prepare for hibernation, grizzlies must prepare a den, and consume an immense amount of food as they do not eat during hibernation. Grizzly bears do not defecate or urinate throughout the entire hibernation period. The male grizzly bear's hibernation ends in early to mid-March, while females emerge in April or early May.

Reproduction: Except for females with cubs, grizzlies are normally solitary, active animals, but in coastal areas, grizzlies gather around streams, lakes, rivers, and ponds during the salmon spawn. Females (sows) produce one to four young (usually two) that are small and weigh only about 450 grams (1 lb) at birth. A sow is protective of her offspring and will attack if she thinks she or her cubs are threatened.
Grizzly bears have one of the lowest reproductive rates of all terrestrial mammals in North America. This is due to numerous ecological factors. Grizzly bears do not reach sexual maturity until they are at least five years old.

Diet: Although grizzlies are of the order Carnivora and have the digestive system of carnivores, they are normally omnivores: their diets consist of both plants and animals.

More. . . https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/125461-Ursus-arctos-horribilis

Photo 1. The longest hair in the photo is 17.7 cm long (7.25 inches). 
Photo 2. Root of longest hair.
Photo 3. Mid portion of longest hair.
Photo 4. Tip of longest hair.
Photo 5.  Entrance to tree hollow. Hollow about 90 cm (3  feet) in diameter.

I found an online resource looking at the fur of Alaskan animals and the closest I could match these hairs with  was the wolverine. I also thought it was possible it might be skunk, but apparently there are no skunks on Vancouver Island.

I am hoping there is a mammal hair expert out there who can help confirm this tentative id.
